    />

        <h2>Why Kanha National Park Is Famous</h2>

        <p>
          Kanha's reputation rests on three pillars: tiger conservation, Barasingha revival, and cinematic landscapes.
          The park was among the first nine tiger reserves established under Project Tiger in 1973, when India's wild
          tiger population had dwindled to crisis levels. Today, Kanha stands as a global conservation success story.
        </p>

        <h3>The Barasingha Conservation Story</h3>
        <p>
          The hard-ground Barasingha (Rucervus duvaucelii branderi) is a subspecies found only at Kanha. By 1970, the
          population had crashed to just 66 animals due to habitat loss and disease. Through dedicated conservation
          efforts — including habitat management, veterinary care, and breeding programs — the population has recovered
          to over 800 individuals. Visitors to Kanha today can see herds of Barasingha grazing in the meadows of
          Kanha Zone, particularly around the Sonph meadows and the Maasahi zone.
        </p>

        <h3>The Jungle Book Connection</h3>
        <p>
          The broader forests of the Satpura-Maikal landscape, including areas adjacent to Kanha, are believed to have
          inspired Rudyard Kipling's 1894 novel "The Jungle Book." The Seoni forests near Kanha are widely associated
          with Mowgli's jungle, lending the park cultural recognition beyond its ecological importance.
        </p>

