        <h2>Kanha Safari Zones</h2>

        <p>
          The park is divided into four safari zones, each with distinct terrain, wildlife density, and access routes.
          Most visitors experience two zones during a 3-day stay.
        </p>

        <h3>Kanha Zone (Accessed via Khatia Gate)</h3>
        <p>
          The most popular zone, covering the core Hallon and Banjar meadows. Famous for Barasingha sightings and reliable
          tiger activity near waterholes. Distance from Khatia Gate: 0-15 km inside the park.
        </p>

        <h3>Kisli Zone (Accessed via Khatia Gate)</h3>
        <p>
          Dense Sal forests with multiple water sources. Known for tiger and leopard sightings along the Kisli road.
          Distance from Khatia Gate: 15-30 km inside the park.
        </p>

        <h3>Mukki Zone (Accessed via Mukki Gate)</h3>
        <p>
          Highest tiger density among all zones. Mukki is 60 km south of Khatia Gate, requiring a separate permit.
          Known for consistent tiger sightings, particularly around the Alikatta and Bhaisanghat areas.
        </p>

        <h3>Sarhi Zone (Accessed via Sarhi Gate)</h3>
        <p>
          The smallest and least-visited zone, ideal for birdwatching and quieter experiences. Sarhi Gate is 30 km
          east of Khatia Gate.
        </p>

        <h2>Geography and Terrain</h2>

        <p>
          Kanha sits on the Maikal Range at the edge of the Deccan plateau. The terrain combines flat-bottomed valleys
          (locally called "dadars") with gentle hills. The elevation ranges from 600 to 900 meters above sea level, with
          the highest point at Sulkum Dongar (924m). The park's landscape includes:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sal forests</strong> — Dominant tree cover across all zones</li>
          <li><strong>Bamboo thickets</strong> — Especially in Kanha and Mukki zones</li>
          <li><strong>Meadows (Dadars)</strong> — Iconic grasslands like Hallon, Banjar, Sonph, Maasahi</li>
          <li><strong>Rivers and streams</strong> — Banjar, Sulkum, Sonph are key water sources</li>
          <li><strong>Plateau highlands</strong> — Sulkum Dongar and other elevated areas</li>
        </ul>

        <Newsletter />

        <h2>Climate and Best Time to Visit</h2>

        <p>
          Kanha experiences three distinct seasons. The park is closed during the southwest monsoon (July-September)
          when heavy rainfall makes safari tracks impassable and coincides with tiger breeding cycles.
        </p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Season</th><th>Months</th><th>Temperature</th><th>Tiger Sightings</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Winter</td><td>Nov–Feb</td><td>10°C–25°C</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Summer</td><td>Mar–May</td><td>25°C–45°C</td><td>High</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Monsoon</td><td>Jun–Sep</td><td>25°C–35°C</td><td>Park Closed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Post-Monsoon</td><td>Oct</td><td>20°C–30°C</td><td>Good</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>How to Reach Kanha National Park</h2>

        <p>
          Kanha is well-connected by air, rail, and road from major Indian cities. The nearest airport is Jabalpur (165 km,
          4 hours by road), with Jabalpur Junction and Gondia Junction serving as the main railway stations. Most visitors
          hire a taxi from these points for the final drive to Khatia Gate.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>By Air:</strong> Jabalpur Airport (JLR) – 165 km | Nagpur (NAG) – 250 km | Raipur (RPR) – 220 km</li>
          <li><strong>By Train:</strong> Jabalpur Junction – 165 km | Gondia Junction – 120 km | Mandla – 90 km</li>
          <li><strong>By Road:</strong> Well-maintained highways from Jabalpur (4 hrs), Nagpur (5-6 hrs), Indore (10 hrs)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Accommodation Near Kanha</h2>

        <p>
          Resorts cluster around Khatia Gate (the main entry), with options ranging from budget homestays to luxury jungle
          lodges. Wildmark Resort, located less than 1 km from the gate, offers mid-range AC accommodation with
          multi-cuisine dining, a swimming pool, and bundled safari packages. Most resorts arrange safari permits,
          jeep bookings, and guide coordination as part of their stay packages.
        </p>

